I wanna ask about the importance of recall as well as accuracy especially when we build a model to predict whether someone has a disease or not. I have 2 scenarios here and i am pretty confused about which one is better:
Case 1:
precision = 0.10
recall = 0.95
f1 = 0.18
accuracy = 0.53
Case 2:
precision = 0.12
recall = 0.13
f1 = 0.12
accuracy = 0.90
i know it's essential to get high score on recall since we don't want to predict someone has no disease but actually he has. so, with accuracy 0.53 in case 1, is it good enough or terrible? or accuracy 0.90 is better although it has less recall score
thanks all!

Recall calculates the number of actual positives your model could predict. Better accuracy is always welcome, but it actually depends on your motto of work. In case 2, the accuracy is better, but recall is very poor. For medical reports, it's not at all good. In case 1, recall is better, but the overall score or accuracy is not impressive. That's not good either. So if I summarize my words, I would say that which metrics you should choose is dependent on your work objective.
Also, the cases seem to be very weird and biased somehow, because a good accuracy with such a poor recall/precision is not a normal thing we generally get to see.

I am a little bit confused about the accuracy you have obtained in the second experiment.
According to 0.12 precision - 88% of the ill patients were predicted as healthy.
According to 0.13 precision - 87% of healthy patients were predicted as ill.
How do you obtain 90% ACC (which means that only 1 out of 10 patients were incurred predicted)? Aren't your classifier inverted? What is your ROC curve does look like?
Recently, I have published a hands-on notebook about ROC curves explanation - please, take a look at it - ROC AUC curve explained | Do it with your own hands. Hope, you will find it useful for you. 
The most interesting thing about the ROC curve in your second example - is what the curve does look like. If it follows a diagonal line - your classifier has poor accuracy. If your curve deviates significantly from diagonal - you have a good model (note, that it doesn't matter in what direction it deviates. If you predict 0 as 1 and 1 as 0 - you have a good binary classifier, just invert an output and you will get good accuracy). Is it your case in the second example?

Hi @mfaaris Regarding the F1, well, considering your results, it's just a typical F1: low in both scenarios!
Why?
Because F1 score, by construction, is a pessimistic scorer. I think this is quite revealing but caution should be taken if used for optimization. Let me explain.
You see, F1 score uses the harmonic mean between recall and precision. As you know, those metrics use false positives and false negatives as part of their metric. Typically, we want those metrics behave good (high), in order to avoid high accuracy bad model phenomena.
Now, the magic relies precisely in the use of the harmonic mean as part of the formula. As you know, if you enhance the model's precision, the recall will fall. and viceversa.
By using the harmonic mean, it'll return close to the worst between the two. That's how harmonic mean behaves. Even when the harmonic mean name has the word mean inside, its results don't make much sense to our regular understanding of means. So for example, if recall=0.5 and precision=0.6 => f1=~0.5. If recall=0.6 and precision=0.5 => f1=~0.5 again! 
Lastly, what'll happen if you optimize a model with F1 score as objective? Clearly, it'll try to maximize the F1 score, which means that it'll try to maximize both precision and recall (contrary forces), but that may mean overfitting as a result, so caution with that.
If you want to understand more harmonic (and geometric) means, this article helped me a lot.

Before beginning with the techniques let us see what do you mean by imputation and why basically we need it.
So let us first understand imputation meaning and cause due to which we need it.
Imputation is a technique to interchange the missing value with the imputed value from a selected technique, like average, median, etc. Missing data occur often within the survey and longitudinal analysis. Incomplete data are problematic, notably within the presence of considerable absent data or systematic non-response patterns.
And we need imputation because of the fact that in the real world there are many missing values present in the dataset and to work on any dataset you need to fill up these missing values.
So, now I hope you understand the meaning of imputation and its use. So let us now see types of imputation techniques with the help of figure.

So in this part 1, we are going to discuss CCA and all the handling missing numerical data techniques, and the rest we will discuss in part 2.
Complete Case Analysis (CCA)
Complete case investigation (CCA), otherwise called list-wise cancellation, is the most fundamental method for dealing with missing information. In CCA, you just move every one of the lines or records where any section or then again field contains missing data. Just those records are handled where genuine data is available for every one of the sections (columns) in the dataset. CCA can be applied to deal with both mathematical furthermore, categorical missing data.
Mean or Median Imputation
This imputation consists of substituting all occurrences of missing values (NAN) at intervals a variable with the mean or median of that variable.
In this imputation, some points to think while implementing this method is:
● If the variable follows a standard distribution, the mean of that column is used to substitute missing values.
● If the variable encompasses a skew distribution, then the median is used for substituting missing values.
Assumptions of Mean or Median Imputation
● Data is missing randomly.
● The missing observations possibly appear as if the bulk of the observations is within the variable.
Advantages of Mean or Median Imputation
● Easy to implement.
● The fast approach of getting complete datasets.
● It is employed in production, i.e throughout model readying.
Limitationsof Mean or Median Imputation
● It distorts the first variable distribution and variance.
● It distorts the variance with the remaining dataset variables.
● The higher the share of missing values, the upper the distortions.
End of Tail Imputation
The end of tail imputation roughly adores arbitrary value imputation; however, it automatically selects the arbitrary values at the tip of the variable distributions.
Here are ways to pick out absolute values:
● If the variable follows a traditional distribution, we will use the mean plus or minus three times the quality deviation.
● If the variable is inclined(skewed), we will use the IQR proximity rule.
For Normal Distribution:
Most of the observations (~99%) of a normally-distributed variable lie inside the mean plus/minus thrice standard deviations—for that the selected value = mean ± three ×standard deviations.
For Skewed Distributions:
The general approach is to calculate the quantiles, then the inter-quantile range (IQR), as follows:
● IQR = seventy-fifth Quantile –twenty-fifth Quantile.
● Upper limit = seventy-fifth Quantile + IQR ×3.
● Lower limit = twenty-fifth Quantile - IQR ×3.
Arbitrary Value Imputation
Arbitrary value imputation consists of replacing all occurrences of missing values (NA) at intervals of a variable with an arbitrary value. The arbitrary value ought to show a discrepancy from the mean or median and not at intervals the traditional values of the
variable. We can use arbitrary values like zero, 999, -999 (or different mixtures of 9s), or -1 (if the distribution is positive).
Assumptionsof Arbitrary Value Imputation
● Data isn't missing randomly.
Advantages of Arbitrary Value Imputation
● Easy to implement.
● It’s a quick way to acquire complete datasets.
● They are often employed in production, i.e throughout model preparation.
● It captures the importance of a worth being “missing” if there's one.
Limitations of Arbitrary Value Imputation
● Distortion of the original variable distribution and its variance.
● Distortion of the variance with the remaining dataset variables.
● If the capricious price is at the tip of the distribution, it should mask or produce outliers.
● We have to watch out to not select an arbitrary value to the same as the mean or median (or the other typical price of the variable distribution).

how to learn R

CLUSTERING
Clustering comes under the domain of Unsupervised Learning . 
Clustering is the task of dividing the population or data points into a number of groups such that data points in the same groups are more similar to other data points in the same group than those in other groups. In simple words, the aim is to segregate groups with similar traits and assign them into clusters.
K-Means Clustering
Kmeans algorithm is basically an iterative algorithm . 
It divides the dataset into k clusters / subgroups , on the basis of similarity and their mean distances from the centroid of that particular cluster . 
How to determine the value of K ( no. of clusters ) ?
For this task concept of WCSS ( Within Cluster Sum of Squares ) and Elbow method is used .
WCSS is the sum of squared distance between each point and centroid in that cluster . So when we plot the graph between k-values and corresponding WCSS values we get a graph which is almost in a shape like elbow , as shown below : 
https://www.google.com/url?sa=i&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.analyticsvidhya.com%2Fblog%2F2021%2F01%2Fin-depth-intuition-of-k-means-clustering-algorithm-in-machine-learning%2F&psig=AOvVaw2uP5sQiHLyjqkP37-dKprK&ust=1643785353090000&source=images&cd=vfe&ved=0CAsQjRxqFwoTCICu4uT33fUCFQAAAAAdAAAAABAD
We go for that K-value from which the WCSS values either starts decreasing with a very slow rate or is almost constant . 
The basic idea behind this method is that it plots the various values of cost with changing k. As the value of K increases, there will be fewer elements in the cluster. So average distortion will decrease. The lesser number of elements means closer to the centroid. So, the point where this distortion declines the most is the elbow point.
Disadvantage of Elbow method :
The elbow method just gives an orientation where the optimal number of k might be, but it is a very subjective method and for some data sets it might not work.  Despite finding an optimal k there is also another problem: We do not have a fixed data set and therefore we don't know if k is a static number.
**Alternative to Elbow Method : **
Silhouette Method : The silhouette Method is also a method to find the optimal number of clusters and interpretation and validation of consistency within clusters of data. The silhouette method computes silhouette coefficients of each point that measure how much a point is similar to its own cluster compared to other clusters. by providing a succinct graphical representation of how well each object has been classified.

Many major universities use R to teach undergrad statistics and data mining in their statistics and data science programs.  Why? My local university uses R for undergrad statistics and R and MatLab for graduate level courses. Many online courses use R to teach introductory statistics.   Data science is much more that just writing code and choosing between R and Python.  Data science programs require multiple statistics courses, calculus, and linear algebra.  R is great for statistics, analytics, and visualization. Hi @michaelzabolocki,

I tried the planar multi-electrode arrays (MEA) myself and the waveform resolution is not clear as with invasive techniques (i.e., sharp electrodes and silicon probes). 
comparison with spikes from other tissues (i.e., human fetal brain) will not make much sense since the electrical signature of the spike depended strongly not only on the density of Na/K channels along the dendritic tree but also on the cellular morphology which is very different in organoids. 
In general, I am not a big supporter of cell classification based on RNA-seq data, especially when we're talking about cells that are closed to stem cells than to mature neurons. It is a long discussion, but for us, neurophysiologist, the definition of a neuronal type include not only the expression of a combination of genes but more importantly results from an anatomical, morphological, electrochemical, circuit, and functional identification, (i.e. a Basquet cell in the hippocampus and in the cerebellum are the same type and perform different tasks).

The transgene expression was not difficult. Even if only a few cells are fluorescently labeled, the most difficult part is to combine simultaneously patch-clamp and extracellular (i.e. , ground-truth experiment, see here). There're only a few such recording sets only performed in rodents (see for example Henze et al., j neurophysiol 2000).

I have some basic knowledge of Tensorflow, since I am working with that for quite a long time. Recently, I am trying to work with Pytorch, but not getting any understanding of it really. The codes of notebooks by others seem very unfamiliar to me. How can I get rid of this? Can you share some resources to learn at least the basics within a short time?
On another note, which one is good to keep up with for the industry and research purposes? Do I really need to learn both?

A lot of people recommend this book - "Deep Learning with PyTorch" by Eli Stevens, Luca Antiga, Thomas Viehmann.
My subjective opinion - PyTorch bits TensorFlow in terms of debugging as well as the ability to quickly change some tensors (yes, I am talking about the assignment to tensor slices hell in TF). In contrast to PyTorch - TensorFlow provides a really good infrastructure around the model - tf.data pipelines, well-designed default training routines, callbacks, losses, built-in tensorboard, and so on. Besides research infrastructure there are TfLite, TFX - you name it. One more thing I hate PyTorch - its documentation. Every time I need to read about a specific function I should scroll miles of documentation pages unless I found an interesting function. Why don't they structure documentation by modules?
Nevertheless, most people prefer PyTorch for research and event industry proposes.

Hi @utshabkumarghosh 
After the release of Tensorflow 2.X, I personally feel Tensorflow is much faster in building the models and trying out experiments. But if you are working on the research side and you need to use custom losses and customize modeling then according to me PyTorch is a really good option. 
You can see a simple linear model in pytorch: https://atrisaxena.github.io/tutorial/Linear_regression-Gradient_descent/ 
There are various tutorials on official Pytorch website: https://pytorch.org/tutorials/index.html 
You don't need to learn both while basic you can learn from both. 

  If you working close to industry you need efficient model deployment on Cloud or Mobile then you can use Tensorflow while if you are more of research person then I think you can use Pytorch.

I started my Deep learning with Tensorflow about a month back. Now when I needed to learn Torch for one of my projects I found it extremely different from what Tensorflow is. In TensorFlow the way we build models is very different, for example, you need a loop in PyTorch whereas in Tensorflow specifying epochs in model.fit does the job. Even Forward Passing and Back Propagation is very different and I find tf to be a better framework.  I recently had a word with one of my seniors about the question that do I need to learn about both these frameworks and he was of the strong opinion that you must know PyTorch and tf should be your 2nd choice. (Idk why 😓). A lot of people believe that PyTorch gives a lot of flexibility and dynamism and tf is like a well-orchestrated mechanism and infrastructure for gathering components and shipping models into production.

I am not sure if we can determine which framework should be first, and which one - 2nd. In rare cases, you start a DL project from scratch. Usually, you start with baseline models implemented in one of those frameworks. That's why you should be familiar both with TF and PyTorch.

PyTorch can be difficult to start with because it is very Pythonic and requires good knowledge of Python class class and deep learning functionality.
From my experience, I feel Keras is good and highly used in the industry. With regard to research papers, Keras codes are generally available within weeks of release so it is good choice.

What is the intuition behind applying dot product on 2 vectors, in machine learning and data science? For instance, why do we apply dot product on the item vector and user vector in content-based filtering (recommender systems)?

Hi @maanassiraj !
Dot product can be viewed as a measure of similarity between the directions of vectors, given that vectors that have an angle between them of 0 (meaning the same vector) have cos(0) = 1, thus their dot product is just a product of their lengths. Other angles result in cos(angle) smaller, so they are less similar. 
This applies in the context of content-based filtering where the dot product of item vector and user vector tells us if they are similar, and if they are, there might be a higher chance of a person being interested in the item than an item with a lower dot product result.
